HEADWORD: Dravidian
<hw>Dra*vid"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[From Skr.
<ets>Dr⟦amac⟧vi⟦dsdot⟧a</ets>, the name of the southern portion of the
peninsula of India.]</ety> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to
the Dravida.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dravidian languages</b></col>, <cd>a group of languages
of Southern India, which seem to have been the idioms of the natives,
before the invasion of tribes speaking Sanskrit. Of these languages, the
Tamil is the most important; Telegu, Malayalam, and Kannada are
included. These languages are distinct from the Indo-European family of
languages.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dravidic</ent>⟦br⟧
